   <h1>Re: [VB] Front beam from 75 to 66</h1>
   <b>&quot;S Hedberg&quot; &lt;shedberg51_at_hotmail_dot_com&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2001-05-22 21:06:27+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>[...]
Isn't this beam higher than the one currently on the 66?  And if so will you 
be lowering it a little to correct for that?

>From: Adrian Pillow <Apillow_at_manh_dot_com>
>To: "Vintage Bus Mailing List (E-mail)" <vintagebus_at_lenti.type2_dot_com>
>CC: "Dave Easterwood (E-mail)" <deasterw_at_mindspring_dot_com>,        "John 
>Baker (E-mail)" <jbakerccymca_at_springmail_dot_com>
>Subject: [VB] Front beam from 75 to 66
>Date: Tue, 22 May 2001 16:04:47 -0400
>
>In a greater effort to enhance the braking power of my '66 I have decided 
>to
>attempt (notice the word attempt) to put a front beam from a '75 bus into a
>'66 bus.  Apparently this is a fairly straight forward process, but want to
>run through the steps with you all before I miss something huge.  I like 
>the
>idea of ball-joints, disc brakes, and dual chamber master cylinder...  My 
>MC
>is shot right now so it is a good excuse also to update instead of just
>replace.
>
>There is some disagreement that the '75 front beam will attach into the 
>four
>17mm bolt holes on the '66 correctly.  I have seen many people on the list
>claim success so I think it can be done.  If it is close the holes can
>always be grinded out to fit if necessary, they have got to be somewhat
>close to begin with.
>
>In random order here are the disassembly steps:
>1.  Take speedo cable off.
>2.  Disconnect the E-brake cables.
>3.  Disconnect drag link.
>4.  Disconnect some other link down there which should be obvious.
>5.  Remove hard brake lines from the master cylinder.
>6.  Remove the beam by removing the 4 bolts on each side.  Load on jack and
>put in supports so I do not crush myself :)
>6.  Remove MC
>7.  Follow steps from Eric and Barb to trim the MC rod for the DC MC in 
>Type
>2 Library.
>8.  Get brake fluid reservoir from a Rabbit (or a '67 good luck!).
>
>Assembly in semi-order:
>1.  Put in new DC MC with adjusted rod.
>2.  Connect rear brakes hard line into the MC.
>3.  Put on the Rabbit fluid reservoir.
>4.  Put beam in place and secure by the 8 bolts.
>5.  Connect hard lines for the front brakes.  (Also check rubber lines,
>pads, and rotors for condition)
>6.  Reattach the drag link and other misc link.
>7.  Connect and readjust E-brake cables.
>8.  Connect speedo cable.
>9.  Bleed the darn brakes again!!!  Arg!
>10.  Go for a spin.
>11.  Have a beer, relax, and let the wife complain at you how badly you 
>just
>wasted a weekend :)
>
>
>Also if I have the '75 rear brakes is there any updates I can do to the 
>rear
>brakes of my '66 while I am at it?  I hate adjusting those darn drums!
>
>A special thank you goes to John Baker for giving the '75 up for adoption 
>in
>the first place!  Thanks, it is being used to help save a '71 and upgrade a
>'66!  Hopefully it can help others in the long run by more parts donations
>for the needy busses.
>
>
>TIA!,
>Adrian Pillow
>1966 VW Microbus Westfalia Hardtop - Biscuit
>1979 Porsche 911 SC
>
>Robin Hood was a thief.
>
>
>
>-------------------------------------------------------------------------
>For help leaving the list, send a HELP message to
>VINTAGEBUS-REQUEST_at_TYPE2.COM
>-------------------------------------------------------------------------
>

